is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "superoxide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.999722421169281, "span": {"begin": 664, "end": 674}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010100"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "oxygen", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9996341466903687, "span": {"begin": 694, "end": 700}}, {"id": ["mesh:D009569"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "NO", "obj": "drug", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 719, "end": 721}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4846"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "eNOS", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9933661818504333, "span": {"begin": 741, "end": 745}}, {"id": ["mesh:D010900"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "endothelial dysfunction", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9997744560241699, "span": {"begin": 777, "end": 800}}, {"id": ["mesh:D002318"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "cardiovascular diseases", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9998302459716797, "span": {"begin": 835, "end": 858}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006973"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypertension", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999904632568359, "span": {"begin": 867, "end": 879}}, {"id": ["mim:108725", "mesh:D050197"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "atherosclerosis", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999973773956299, "span": {"begin": 881, "end": 896}}, {"id": ["mesh:D006937"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "hypercholesterolemia", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999924898147583, "span": {"begin": 898, "end": 918}}, {"id": ["mesh:D003920"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "diabetes mellitus", "obj": "disease", "prob": 0.9999982714653015, "span": {"begin": 924, "end": 941}}], "text": "Endothelial nitric oxide synthase (eNOS) is responsible for the generation of vascular nitric oxide (NO), a protective molecule that is involved in the regulation of endothelium-dependent vasodilation, vascular tone, and blood pressure (F&ouml;rstermann and M&uuml;nzel, 2006). To generate NO, eNOS hydroxylates L-arginine to N-hydroxy-L-arginine and then oxidizes N-hydroxy-L-arginine to L-citrulline and NO. This enzymatic process requires NADPH, Ca2+/calmondulin, flavin mononucleotide, flavin adenine dinucleotide and its cofactor tetrahydrobiopterin (BH4). Limiting BH4 levels or S-glutathionylation of eNOS can lead to eNOS uncoupling in which eNOS produces superoxide (or other reactive oxygen species) and less NO. The uncoupling of eNOS has been demonstrated to cause endothelial dysfunction, and is implicated in a number of cardiovascular diseases such as hypertension, atherosclerosis, hypercholesterolemia, and diabetes mellitus (Dumitrescu et al., 2007).", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:38:09 +0000 2026"}